$$
and $Ï‰ = \exp(2Ï€{\rm i}/n)$.

**Proof**
Consider the circulant shift matrix:
$$
\underbrace{
\begin{bmatrix}
0   &&& 1
\\ 1 \\
& â‹± \\ &&1 & 0
\end{bmatrix}
}_S
$$
so that $C = a_0 I  + a_1 S + â‹¯ + a_{n-1} S^{n-1}$. Note $S$ is a permutation matrix, hence it is orthogonal ($S^âŠ¤ S = I$),
normal, and is diagonalisable. We verify directly that $Q_n$ is its eigenvector matrix (use the fact that $Ï‰^{-(n-j)} = Ï‰^j$):
$$
\begin{align*}
S Q_n &= {1 \over âˆšn} \begin{bmatrix} 1 & Ï‰^{-(n-1)} & Ï‰^{-2(n-1)} & â‹¯ & Ï‰^{-(n-1)^2} \\
