### Polynomial multiplication


Consider multiplication of two polynomials of at most degree $n-1$ (if we have polynomials of different degree
we can pad their coefficients to be of the same size), which we can write in matrix form in terms of a Toeplitz
matrix (one with constant diagonals):
$$
\begin{align*}
a(z)b(z) = \left(âˆ‘_{k=0}^{n-1} a_k z^k\right) \left(âˆ‘_{j=0}^{n-1} b_j z^j\right) = 
âˆ‘_{k=0}^{n-1} âˆ‘_{j=0}^{n-1} a_k b_j z^{k+j}  \\
= \underbrace{
\begin{bmatrix}
a_0 \\ 
a_1 & a_0 \\ 
â‹® & â‹± & â‹± \\ 
a_{n-2} & â‹¯ & a_1 & a_0\\
a_{n-1} & a_{n-2} & â‹¯ & a_1 & a_0\\
 &â‹± & â‹± & â‹± & a_1 \\
 && a_{n-1} & a_{n-2} & â‹®\\
 &&& a_{n-1} & a_{n-2} \\
 &&&& a_{n-1} 
\end{bmatrix}}_T
 \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix} b_0 \\ â‹® \\ b_{n-1} \end{bmatrix}}_ğ›
\end{align*}
$$
where $T âˆˆ â„‚^{2n-1 Ã— n}$. (Note the roles of $a$ and $b$ can be swapped due to commutativity,
but for concreteness
we define $T$ in terms of $a$.)
Each row takes $O(n)$ operations to apply so the total cost is $O(n^2)$ operations. We will
see that the FFT can reduce this to $O(n \log n)$.

In particular, we pad $b$ with zeros and pad $T$ on the right to obtain:
$$
a(z) b(z) = T ğ› = \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}
a_0 & & &  & & a_{n-1} & â‹¯ & a_2 & a_1 \\ 
a_1 & a_0 &&&&& a_{n-1} & â‹¯ & a_2 \\
â‹® & â‹± & â‹± &&&&& â‹± &  â‹® \\ 
a_{n-2} & â‹¯ & a_1 & a_0 &&&&& a_{n-1}  \\ 
a_{n-1} & a_{n-2} & â‹¯ & a_1 & a_0\\
 &â‹± & â‹± & â‹± & a_1 & a_0 \\
 && a_{n-1} & a_{n-2} & â‹® & â‹± & â‹± \\
 &&& a_{n-1} & a_{n-2}  & â‹¯ & a_1 & a_0\\
 &&&& a_{n-1} & a_{n-2} & â‹¯ & a_1 & a_0
\end{bmatrix}}_C \begin{bmatrix} ğ› \\ ğŸ \end{bmatrix}
$$
that is, $C âˆˆ â„‚^{2n-1 Ã— 2n-1}$ satisfies
$$
\begin{align*}
C[1:2n-1,1:n] = T \\
C[1:n-1,n+1:2n-1] = T[n+1:2n-2,1:n-1] \\
C[n+1:2n-1,n+1:2n-1] = T[1:n-1,1:n-1] 
\end{align*}

$$A = T[1:n,1:n]$ and $B = T[n+1:2n,1:n]$.

Here is a low dimensional example. Suppose we want to multiply 
$$
